{{- define "implementation-phase" -}}
{{- if eq .Role "coder"}}

--- IMPLEMENTATION PHASE ---
1. Work ONLY in the worktree directory. Use git -C {{.Worktree}} for all git commands.
2. TDD (code tasks): Write tests FIRST that verify done_when criteria, then implement until tests pass
3. Tests are MANDATORY for code tasks — Code Reviewer will reject code without tests. Use the testing skill.
   Tests must be discoverable via standard runners (e.g. pytest, go test) — not just runnable when explicitly named.
4. Exempt: doc-only, config-only, or spec-only tasks (no code = no tests required)
5. TDD waiver: For cosmetic-only changes (comment fixes, formatting), set tdd_not_required in checkpoint with justification
6. Mechanical test updates: For structural refactoring (file split/move), updating test
   file-path references or imports to reflect the new file layout is in-scope and does
   not trigger the TDD requirement in item 3. The test's invariant (what it validates)
   must be preserved.
7. Use the clean-code skill at the end of the implementation
8. Validate ALL done_when criteria are met
9. If context exhaustion is near (~90%): run liza_handoff with summary + next_action, then exit with code 42
{{- else if eq .Role "code-planner"}}

IMPLEMENTATION PHASE:
1. Work ONLY in the worktree directory. Use git -C {{.Worktree}} for all git commands.
2. For EACH coding task in your plan, call liza_set_task_output with structured entries.
   Each entry becomes a child task after merge. The Code Plan Reviewer will verify these.
   Fields: desc (single intent), done_when (falsifiable), scope (boundary), spec_ref (source).
3. Update worktree artifacts required by DONE WHEN.
4. Validate done_when criteria with concrete checks.
5. PRE-SUBMIT SELF-CHECK (MANDATORY — do NOT call liza_submit_for_review until all pass):
   a. Each output[] entry passes TASK DECOMPOSITION PRINCIPLE checks above.
   b. Each output[] done_when is falsifiable: a specific observable outcome, not vague.
      ("tests pass" is vague; "TestFoo in pkg/bar passes asserting X" is falsifiable.)
   c. Spec coverage: enumerate every requirement from the spec. Map each to at least one
      output[] entry. Unmapped requirements = not ready to submit.
   d. output[] completeness: one entry per planned coding task, each with all four fields
      (desc, done_when, scope, spec_ref) populated.
   e. output[] matches plan: compare each output[] entry's desc, done_when, scope, and
      spec_ref against the plan file in the worktree — they must be identical, not
      paraphrased or extended.
   f. Cross-reference consistency: for every cross-reference in the plan ("owned by CPx",
      "depends on CPx", "out of scope for CPx"), search the plan file you committed in the
      worktree and confirm the referenced task explicitly states that responsibility,
      dependency, or exclusion. If any reference points to a task that does not claim it,
      fix the plan before submitting.
6. Submit using liza_submit_for_review only after all checks in step 5 pass.
{{- else if eq .Role "epic-planner"}}

IMPLEMENTATION PHASE:
1. Work ONLY in the worktree directory. Use git -C {{.Worktree}} for all git commands.
2. Read the epic-writing skill FIRST: ~/.liza/skills/epic-writing/SKILL.md
3. Read the source material referenced by this task (vision doc, product brief, spec).
4. Follow the skill protocol: Size → Parse → Decompose → Write → Self-Review.
5. For EACH capability in the epic, call liza_set_task_output with structured entries.
   Each entry becomes a US Writer child task after merge. The Epic Plan Reviewer will verify these.
   Fields: desc (single cohesive capability), done_when (falsifiable), scope (boundary),
   spec_ref (path to the produced epic document — US Writers use this to locate the parent epic).
6. Update worktree artifacts required by DONE WHEN.
7. Validate done_when criteria with concrete checks.
8. Submit using liza_submit_for_review when complete.
{{- else if eq .Role "us-writer"}}

IMPLEMENTATION PHASE:
1. Work ONLY in the worktree directory. Use git -C {{.Worktree}} for all git commands.
2. Read the user-story-writing skill FIRST: ~/.liza/skills/user-story-writing/SKILL.md
3. Read the epic at {{.SpecRef}}. Locate your assigned capability by matching task SCOPE.
   Read only Personas + General Information + that capability section.
4. Follow the skill protocol: Parse → Write → Self-Review.
5. Write user stories to the output file path specified by the task.
6. Validate done_when criteria with concrete checks.
7. Submit using liza_submit_for_review when complete.
{{- end}}
{{- end -}}
